1. WHAT CCON: IS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  CCON: is a mounted console handler - the same kind of thing CON:,
  KingCON and ViNCEd are. You mount it once, and from then on any
  program can open a console window through it, exactly as it would
  through CON:.

  The reason it exists is OUTPUT SCROLLBACK. The stock 3.2 console
  has none, and cannot be given any from the outside: commands talk
  to the handler, so a terminal program cannot bolt scrollback on.
  CCON: keeps 1000 lines of history behind every window by
  default (LINES=n asks for more, up to 4000).

  Around that core it grew into a full console with a modern shell
  feel:

    - every open gets its OWN window, stock CON: fashion
    - a real AmigaShell runs in it (NewShell CCON:)
    - fish-style autosuggestions from your command history
    - zsh-style tab completion with a cycling menu
    - bash-style Ctrl+R incremental history search
    - readline line surgery (Ctrl+W/U/K/L)
    - scrollback by keys and mouse wheel, in raw mode too
    - copy and paste with the stock console, both directions,
      with double-click word and triple-click line selection
    - SGR colour with a careful ANSI/Workbench pen separation,
      plus real italic/underline/inverse soft styles
    - FONT and LINES per window: your own font and scrollback
      depth, or Font Prefs' default font if you don't ask
    - fullscreen programs work: Ed with working menus, More -
      and More leaves your scrollback transcript as it found it,
      xterm-alternate-screen style
    - a raw twin device, CRAW:, for RAW:-style uses


2. REQUIREMENTS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  AmigaOS 3.2. Boot-verified on 3.2 with a 68030 (FS-UAE).
  Older OS versions are untested.

  CCON: deliberately answers the 3.2 shell's console probe in a way
  that makes the shell hand line editing to the console - that is
  where the history, completion, ghosts and search live.

  Memory: each window allocates its scrollback model at open time,
  roughly 235K at 80 columns and the default 1000 lines (LINES=n
  scales it directly, up to 4000). Plenty on an expanded machine;
  mind it on a 2MB one.


3. INSTALLATION
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  From the archive (the drawers mirror SYS:):

    copy L/ccon-handler L:
    copy DEVS/CCON-mountlist DEVS:
    copy DEVS/CRAW-mountlist DEVS:
    Mount CCON: FROM DEVS:CCON-mountlist
    Mount CRAW: FROM DEVS:CRAW-mountlist

  Add the two Mount lines to S:User-Startup to make them permanent.

  Try it:

    NewShell CCON:
    echo >CCON:0/0/300/80/hi/WAIT hello
    type S:Startup-sequence >CRAW:0/0/500/150/t/WAIT

  A note on updating: a running handler keeps its loaded code. After
  replacing L:ccon-handler, reboot - a re-Mount alone is not enough.


4. OPENING WINDOWS: THE NAME SYNTAX
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  The open name is stock CON: syntax. Every field may be left empty
  and options may come in any order:

    CCON:x/y/width/height/title/option/option/...

  Examples:

    NewShell CCON:
    NewShell CCON:60/30/500/120/My-Shell
    dir >CCON:0/0/400/200/dir/WAIT
    echo >CCON:0/0/300/80/log/AUTO/WAIT starting...

  width or height of -1 fills the screen it opens on:

    NewShell CCON:0/0/-1/-1
    NewShell CCON:0/0/-1/300

  EVERY open gets its own console and window, exactly as with stock
  CON:. A redirect like `list >CCON:` opens (and, without WAIT,
  closes) a window of its own. The window closes when the last
  handle on it closes.

  Opens of `*` and of CONSOLE: attach to the console the calling
  program is already running on, instead of making a new window.
  This is how a command reopens its own shell window.


5. THE OPTIONS, ONE BY ONE
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  CLOSE      Put a close gadget on the window. The gadget is ON by
             default (like a 3.2 shell window); clicking it sends
             end-of-file to the program reading the window.

  NOCLOSE    Remove the close gadget.

  WAIT       Keep the window open after the last handle closes,
             until its close gadget is clicked. Without it, output
             windows flash by:  dir >CCON:0/0//200/d/WAIT

  AUTO       The open succeeds without a window; the window only
             appears on the first actual I/O. The classic idiom for
             debug consoles that should not open until they have
             something to say.

  SCREENname Open on the named public screen, e.g. SCREENWorkbench
             or a terminal's own screen name.

  NOBORDER   No window border.
  NODRAG     No drag bar.
  NODEPTH    No depth gadget.
  NOSIZE     No sizing gadget.
  BACKDROP   A backdrop window.
  INACTIVE   Do not activate the window on open.

  WINDOW0xADDR
             Render into an EXISTING window at that address instead
             of opening one. This is how a terminal program hands
             its frame window to CCON:. The window is returned to
             its owner untouched on close.

  PENn       Default text pen number, 1-15. A terminal with an ANSI
             palette typically passes PEN7.

  WBPENS     Declares the screen's palette truly ANSI. Plain SGR
             30-33 from programs are then treated as WORKBENCH pen
             numbers and retargeted at the theme (C:Ed hardcodes
             WB pens; without this it would render in ANSI red).
             See section 14 for the full colour story.

  FONTname/size
             Open the window in this font, loading it from disk if
             it is not already resident. Left unset, the window
             opens in whatever font Font Prefs has set as "System
             Default Text" (topaz 8 only if that font can't be
             opened, or is proportional - proportional fonts don't
             fit the cell model). Example: FONTmicroknight/8.

  LINESn     How many lines of scrollback THIS window keeps
             (default 1000, floor 100, ceiling 4000). Raise it for
             a deep transcript, lower it on a tight machine - see
             section 15 for the cost per line.

  Not implemented: SMART, SIMPLE, ALT, ICONIFY.

  A WARNING WORTH BOLD: the AmigaDOS shell eats an unquoted '='
  from ANY command line before CCON: ever sees it - so a FONT or
  LINES option MUST be written without one (FONTtopaz/8, LINES200),
  or the whole open string quoted. `FONT=topaz/8` silently truncates
  to `FONT` and does nothing; this is a shell fact, not a CCON: bug.

  A keyword as the very FIRST field switches the whole open string
  to options-only, with default position and size - so a plain
  option needs no throwaway slashes:

    NewShell CCON:FONTtopaz/8
    NewShell CCON:WAIT
    NewShell CCON:LINES200

  Mixing geometry WITH options still needs the full positional form
  (x/y/w/h/title come first, as in section 4):

    NewShell CCON:0/0/640/200/My-Window/FONTtopaz/8


6. THE LINE EDITOR
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  Cooked mode - the shell prompt - is edited by the console:

    typing            inserts at the cursor
    Left / Right      move by one character
    Ctrl+Left/Right   jump by word
    Shift+Left/Right  jump to start / end of line
    Backspace         delete before the cursor
    Del               delete under the cursor
    Esc               clear the line
    Return            commit the line
    Up / Down         walk the history (32 entries; the half-typed
                      line is stashed and comes back)
    Ctrl+W            delete the word before the cursor
    Ctrl+U            delete from line start to the cursor
    Ctrl+K            delete from the cursor to line end
    Ctrl+L            clear the screen, keeping the line - the
                      cleared rows scroll into HISTORY, so Shift+Up
                      brings them back; nothing is destroyed
    Ctrl+\            end-of-file (EndShell on an interactive shell)
    Ctrl+C..F         break signals to the running command, as on
                      any Amiga console

  Long lines wrap across rows like the stock shell: growing past
  the bottom of the window scrolls the screen, and the prompt walks
  up with it.


7. AUTOSUGGESTIONS (THE GREY GHOST)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  As you type, CCON: looks for the newest history entry that begins
  with your line (case-blind) and shows the rest of it as grey
  ghost text at the cursor:

    4.Work:> ls _-la AmigaTools/        <- "-la AmigaTools/" is
                                           grey: a suggestion

    Right / Shift+Right   accept the whole suggestion
    Ctrl+Right            accept ONE word of it (leading space
                          included: from `ls`, one stroke takes
                          ` -la`)
    anything else         just keep typing; the ghost adapts or
                          disappears

  The ghost is display only. It is never part of what Return
  commits, never copied by a selection, and it only appears at all
  on screens that have a readable grey pen - a ghost that looked
  like typed text would be worse than none.

  Tab never accepts the ghost - it always opens tab completion
  (below), ghost or no ghost. Ghosts are a Right-family thing only.


8. TAB COMPLETION
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  Tab completes the word at the cursor as a filename:

    - one match: completed fully; a directory gets a trailing '/',
      a file a trailing space
    - several matches: completed to the common prefix, then a MENU
      of candidates opens below the prompt

  In the menu:

    Tab          cycle forward
    Shift+Tab    cycle backwards
    Return       accept the highlighted candidate and close; the
                 line stays put, so a second Return runs it
    Esc          close the menu, line unchanged
    any other    close the menu, then act normally

  Menu colours mirror the ls scheme: directories blue, hidden-class
  entries (h-bit or .info) grey.

  Relative words complete in the current directory of the shell
  that is reading the window; words with ':' resolve through
  assigns, volumes and devices.

  Limits, by design: no quoted words, one menu page (80 candidates;
  a beep means there are more), no volume-name completion for a
  bare word.


9. CTRL+R HISTORY SEARCH
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  Ctrl+R searches your history incrementally, the bash way. The
  prompt itself is replaced by an inverse banner:

    (search: fra_)  matching-command-line

  Type any fragment - it matches ANYWHERE in the line, not just at
  the start (that is the difference from the ghost). The newest
  matching history entry appears in the edit line as you type.

    Ctrl+R (again)   step to the next older match
    Backspace        shorten the fragment (search widens back)
    Return           run the shown match
    cursor keys      keep the match and edit it normally
    Esc              forget it all; your original line comes back

  A beep means no entry matches; the line keeps the last match.
  When the search ends, the real prompt returns - CCON: restores
  it from the scrollback model, pixel for pixel.


10. SCROLLBACK
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  Every window remembers 1000 lines by default (LINESn asks for
  more, up to 4000 - section 5). Viewing:

    Shift+Up / Shift+Down   page back / forward  (cooked mode)
    Ctrl+Up / Ctrl+Down     one line at a time   (ALL modes)
    mouse wheel             three lines a tick   (ALL modes)

  "All modes" means raw mode too: you can wheel back through More's
  display or a fullscreen program's output while it runs. Raw
  programs never see the scroll keys or the wheel.

  While you are back, the title bar shows [scrollback -n]. Any new
  output, or any other key, snaps the view to live. Colours are
  remembered per cell and survive the trip.


11. COPY AND PASTE
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  Selecting:

    drag                  select a range; output FREEZES while you
                          hold the button, exactly like the stock
                          console, and resumes on release
    double-click          select the word under the pointer
    triple-click          select the whole line

  Releasing a drag - or the click selections immediately - copies
  the text to clipboard.device unit 0 as IFF FTXT, the format the
  stock console family uses. So:

    - copy in CCON:, paste in a stock CON: window: works
    - copy in stock CON:, paste in CCON:: works

  Pasting:

    RAMIGA-V   paste the clipboard as typed input. In cooked mode
               it runs through the line editor (a multi-line clip
               executes line by line); in raw mode the program
               receives the bytes (pasting into Ed works).
    RAMIGA-C   re-copy the standing highlight.

  Selection works on the scrollback view as well - scroll back,
  copy an old error, snap live, paste it.

  You can select the line you are still typing; the prompt and the
  edit line are ordinary cells to the selection machinery.


12. RAW MODE AND CRAW:
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  Programs switch a CCON: stream between cooked and raw with the
  usual SetMode/ACTION_SCREEN_MODE - fullscreen programs do this
  themselves. In raw mode every key becomes bytes for the program
  (arrows and F-keys as CSI sequences, Ctrl+C as a plain byte 3),
  and the console shows the classic block cursor.

  CRAW: is the same handler mounted a second time with a startup
  argument that opens every stream raw from the first byte - the
  RAW: counterpart:

    type somefile >CRAW:0/0/500/150/t/WAIT

  Both devices can be mounted and used at the same time; each runs
  as its own handler process.


13. RUNNING FULLSCREEN PROGRAMS (ED, MORE)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  Ed and More work as they do on stock CON:, including the parts
  that usually break on replacement consoles:

    - Ed's MENUS drop and pick. Menu picks travel the same route
      they take over stock CON: (as input events, not IDCMP), which
      is the route Ed is actually written against.
    - Ed re-measures itself when you resize the window.
    - More's single-key paging uses real timed WAIT_CHARs.
    - The block cursor is drawn by the console, as Ed expects.
    - Swedish (and other) dead-key composition works in raw mode.
    - More restores your scrollback transcript exactly as it found
      it on exit: it brackets its session in CSI ?47h / ?47l, the
      same alternate-screen sequence xterm honours, and CCON:
      answers it the same way xterm does - pages you viewed in More
      do not enter your history, and quitting snaps back to your
      prompt instantly, pixel for pixel. Any client that sends the
      same sequence gets the same treatment.

  And unlike stock CON:, Ctrl+Up/Down and the wheel still scroll
  the view while these programs run - except on the alternate
  screen (More mid-page), where scrolling is refused, xterm manners.


14. HOW IT WORKS, BRIEFLY
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  CCON: is a DOS packet handler written in Amiga E. A few of its
  load-bearing choices:

  Keys arrive the way console.device's own do: an input.device
  handler sits just below Intuition in the input chain, takes
  events for the active CCON: window, and runs them through
  keymap.library. If the chain cannot be installed, the handler
  falls back to window (IDCMP) input automatically.

  The 3.2 shell probes each console at startup and, if it likes
  the answer, runs its OWN line editor. CCON: answers the probe so
  the shell leaves editing to the console - which is what makes
  history, ghosts, completion and search possible at the prompt.

  Colour lives in two worlds that must not mix. With WBPENS the
  palette is declared truly ANSI: pen conventions apply as-is and
  bold maps to the bright pens. On any other screen, plain SGR
  30-37 stay raw pen numbers (what Workbench-pen programs like Ed
  mean), while the bold forms - ANSI colour intent, the ls scheme -
  are translated BY COLOUR to the screen's nearest real pens. So
  directories are genuinely blue everywhere, and Ed is never red.

  Each window's display is backed by a scrollback model (1000
  lines by default, LINES=n for more up to 4000) with one
  attribute byte per cell
  plus a style byte for SGR 3/4/7 (italic, underline, inverse -
  inverse is a pen swap at paint time, never a stored colour).
  Redraws, scrollback, selection repaints, menu restores and the
  Ctrl+R prompt restore all read from it.

  A window with no FONT option opens in whatever font Font Prefs
  has set as "System Default Text" - the same font stock CON:
  honours - falling back to topaz 8 only if that font is missing
  or proportional.

  A program that sets its own window title (the xterm-style OSC
  sequence, ESC ] 0 ; title BEL) is remembered as the window's
  title from then on; leaving scrollback restores THAT title, not
  CCON:'s own.

  The window closes with its last handle; WAIT windows linger for
  their gadget. Every open parses its own name, so all options
  apply per window.


15. KNOWN LIMITATIONS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  - The scrollback model costs about 235K per window at 80 columns
    and the default 1000 lines (LINES=n scales this up to 4000,
    or down to a floor of 100).
  - CSI K under a coloured background erases to black.
  - Completion: no quoted words, one menu page, no volume-name
    completion for a bare word.
  - SMART/SIMPLE, ALT and ICONIFY are not implemented.
  - A borrowed window (WINDOW0x) keeps its owner's font; FONT only
    applies to windows CCON: opens itself.


16. BUILDING FROM SOURCE
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  The prebuilt binary is included; nothing needs compiling. To
  build it yourself, with the E-VO E compiler:

    evo ccon-handler.e LARGE

  The LARGE model is required as of 1.0. The source is one file,
  ccon-handler.e, and carries its design history as comments -
  including how an E binary survives being started as a handler,
  verified by disassembling the compiler's generated startup code.


17. FILES
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  L/ccon-handler         the handler
  DEVS/CCON-mountlist    Mount CCON: FROM this
  DEVS/CRAW-mountlist    the raw-by-default second device
  ccon.readme            short-form readme
  ccon.doc               this manual

